Formulation References

The market and dispatch formulations implemented in src/surge-dispatch and
src/surge-market — including SCUC with reactive reserves, branch switching,
soft energy-window slacks, startup/shutdown trajectory power in bus balance,
linearized N-1 security cuts, and the AC reconcile with reactive-reserve
coupling — follow the problem formulation published for the ARPA-E Grid
Optimization (GO) Competition Challenge 3:

Holzer, J. T., Coffrin, C. J., DeMarco, C., Duthu, R., Elbert, S. T.,
Eldridge, B. C., Elgindy, T., Garcia, M., Greene, S. L., Guo, N., Hale, E.,
Lesieutre, B., Mak, T. W., McMillan, C., Mittelmann, H., Oh, H.,
O'Neill, R. P., Overbye, T. J., Palmintier, B., Parker, R., Safdarian, F.,
Tbaileh, A., Van Hentenryck, P., Veeramany, A., Wangen, S., and Wert, J. L.
"Grid Optimization Competition Challenge 3 Problem Formulation."
Pacific Northwest National Laboratory, Report PNNL-35792, April 2024.
DOI: https://doi.org/10.2172/2337844

The companion analysis paper is:

Holzer, J. T., Elbert, S., Mittelmann, H., O'Neill, R., and Oh, H.
"GO Competition Challenge 3: Problem, Solvers, and Solution Analysis."
arXiv:2411.12033 [math.NA], November 2024.
https://arxiv.org/abs/2411.12033

The GO Competition Challenge 3 problem formulation and associated documents
are U.S. Government works prepared by Pacific Northwest National Laboratory
under contract with the U.S. Department of Energy. Competition datasets and
reference winner submissions used internally for validation (under
`target/benchmarks/` and the `benchmarks/go_c3/` dev-only tooling) are
governed by the competition's own data-use terms; no Challenge 3 competitor
source code is included in Surge.
